In order to visualize the hole-transport pathways, we consider a stack of molecules along the a direction of the spiro-OMeTAD crystal, as schematically illustrated in Fig. 4a. Due to the presence of the cross electronic couplings tH/H−1, hole-transport pathways involving both the HOMO and HOMO-1 channels can be expected in the crystal. In order to obtain a simple (but reliable) picture, it was found useful to apply a transformation procedure, leading to a new set of molecular orbitals referred to as HOMO*s and HOMO*-1s, in which the cross electronic couplings are eliminated (i.e., tH/H−1 = 0, see the Supplementary Information); in this way, an effective hole-transport pathway corresponding to a single channel is obtained, as illustrated in Fig. 4b (the effective values of the model parameters after the transformation are collected in Table S3). Since the transformation effectively incorporates the impact of tH/H−1 into other parameters, the values of the new parameters associated with HOMO*s and HOMO*-1s are all changed with respect to those of the original ones; for instance, the values of tH*-1(12)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
